{"title_page": "Diaa Jubaili", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{short description|Iraqi novelist}}\n{{Use British English Oxford spelling|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n|name         = Diaa Jubaili\n|image        = Diaa_Jubaili_Iraqi_Writer.jpg\n|imagesize    =\n|caption      = \n|birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1977|5|23}}\n|birth_place  = [[Basra]]\n|nationality  = {{flag|Iraq}}i\n|education    = \n|occupation   = Writer\n|notableworks = {{plainlist|\n*''No Windmills in Basra''\n*''What To Do Without Calvino?''\n*\"The Worker\" in ''Iraq + 100''\n*\"The Darwinist\" in ''Strange Horizons''}}\n\n|awards = \n*Al-Multaqa Prize for Arabic Short Fiction (2018)\n*Tayeb Salih International Award for Creative Writing (2017)\n*Dubai Culture Award (2007)\n}}\n\n'''Diaa Jubaili''' ({{lang-ar|\u0636\u064a\u0627\u0621 \u062c\u0628\u064a\u0644\u064a}}, (\u1e0c\u012bya Jubayl\u012b); born 23 May 1977) is an [[Iraqis|Iraqi]] novelist and writer from the city of Basra.\n\n==Biography==\nDiaa was born in [[Iraq]] in 1977 in the city of [[Basra]], where he is permanently based.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sci-fi stories envisage Iraq in 100 years|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-37687739|accessdate=2 October 2019|newspaper=BBC News|date=22 October 2016}}</ref> He became a writer and novelist in an environment which did not afford him a traditional education<ref>{{cite interview|last=Jubaili|first=Diaa|interviewer= Heather Sharp, BBC|work=Comma Press Blog|title=Iraq + 100: Diaa Jubaili on short stories and life in Basra (Part 1)|url=https://thecommapressblog.wordpress.com/2016/11/18/iraq-100-diaa-jubailie-on-short-stories-and-life-in-basra-part-1/|accessdate=2 October 2019|publisher=Comma Press|date=18 November 2016}}</ref> and also writes articles about life in Iraq.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pollution and corruption are choking the life out of Basra|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/sep/13/pollution-corruption-choking-life-out-of-basra|accessdate=2 October 2019|newspaper=The Guardian|date=13 September 2018}}</ref> An extensive reading of Western literature is an influence on his work.<ref>{{cite news|title='More story writers in Basra than even in Baghdad'|url=https://yourmiddleeast.com/2016/12/21/ae%CB%9Cmore-story-writers-in-basra-than-even-in-baghdad/|accessdate=2 October 2019|publisher=Your Middle East|date=21 December 2016}}</ref> In his fiction writing, he focuses on questions of identity in Iraq as well as the tension between religion and nationalism.<ref>{{cite news|language=Arabic|title=\u0631\u0648\u0627\u064a\u0629 \"\u0623\u0633\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0635\u0631\u0629\".. \u0639\u0646 \u0634\u062e\u0635\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0627\u0642 \u0627\u0644\u0636\u0627\u0626\u0639\u0629|url=https://www.aljazeera.net/news/cultureandart/2016/7/17/\u0631\u0648\u0627\u064a\u0629-\u0623\u0633\u062f-\u0627\u0644\u0628\u0635\u0631\u0629-\u0639\u0646-\u0634\u062e\u0635\u064a\u0629-\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0627\u0642-\u0627\u0644\u0636\u0627\u0626\u0639\u0629|accessdate=2 October 2019|newspaper=Al Jazeera|date=17 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nDiaa has won literary awards for his writing in Arabic. In 2017, he won the seventh annual Tayeb Salih International Award for Creative Writing for his novel ''What To Do Without Calvino?''.<ref>{{cite news|language=Arabic|title=\u0636\u064a\u0627\u0621 \u062c\u0628\u064a\u0644\u064a.. \u062c\u0627\u0626\u0632\u0629 \u0648\u062b\u0644\u0627\u062b\u0629 \u0643\u062a\u0628|url=https://www.ultrasawt.com/\u062b\u0642\u0627\u0641\u0629/\u0646\u0634\u0631\u0629-\u062b\u0642\u0627\u0641\u064a\u0629/\u0627\u0644\u062a\u0631\u0627-\u0635\u0648\u062a/\u0636\u064a\u0627\u0621-\u062c\u0628\u064a\u0644\u064a-\u062c\u0627\u0626\u0632\u0629-\u0648\u062b\u0644\u0627\u062b\u0629-\u0643\u062a\u0628|accessdate=2 October 2019|newspaper=Ultra Sawt|date=27 February 2017}}</ref> His  short story collection, ''No Windmills in Basra'', won the 2018 [[Al Multaqa Prize]] for the Arabic Short Story. The large prize purse of USD$20,000 is to encourage the short story genre in the Arab world.<ref>{{cite news|title=\nNew Arabic short story prize meets with cautious welcome|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/jan/01/new-arabic-short-story-prize-welcome-almutaqa|accessdate=2 October 2019|newspaper=The Guardian|date=1 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography in [[Arabic]]==\n\nDiaa has released eight novels and three short story collections in Arabic.\n\n=== Novels/Novellas ===\n* 2007: ''Curse of the Marquis''  (\u0644\u0639\u0646\u0629 \u0645\u0627\u0631\u0643\u064a\u0632 ''L\u02bfanat M\u0101rk\u012bz'')\n* 2009: ''The Ugly Face of Vincent'' (novella)  (\u0648\u062c\u0647 \u0641\u0646\u0633\u0646\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0628\u064a\u062d ''Wajh Finsint Alqab\u012b\u1e25'')\n* 2011: ''Bogeys, the Bizarre'' (novella)  (\u0628\u0648\u063a\u064a\u0632 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u062c\u064a\u0628 ''B\u016b\u0121\u012bz il-\u02bfaj\u012bb'')\n* 2014: ''General Stanley Maude's Souvenir''  (\u062a\u0630\u0643\u0627\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u062c\u0646\u0631\u0627\u0644 \u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646\u0644\u064a \u0645\u0648\u062f ''Ta\u1e0fk\u0101r il-jinr\u0101l sit\u0101nl\u012b mawd'')\n* 2016: ''The Lion of Basra''  (\u0623\u0633\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0635\u0631\u0629 ''\u02beasad il-ba\u1e63ra'')\n* 2017: ''The Cloven Man: Six Ways of Crossing Borders Illegally on the Way to Baghdad''  (\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0634\u0637\u0648\u0631, \u0633\u062a \u0637\u0631\u0627\u0626\u0642 \u063a\u064a\u0631 \u0634\u0631\u0639\u064a\u0629 \u0644\u0627\u062c\u062a\u064a\u0627\u0632 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u062f\u0648\u062f \u0646\u062d\u0648 \u0628\u063a\u062f\u0627\u062f ''Al-ma\u0161\u1e6d\u016br, sittu \u1e6dar\u0101\u02beiq \u0121ayr \u0161ar\u02bfiyya li\u02beitiyaz il-\u1e25ud\u016bd na\u1e25u ba\u0121d\u0101d'')\n* 2018: ''Name Upon the Hollow'', (\u0627\u0644\u0627\u0633\u0645 \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u062e\u0645\u0635 ''Al-\u02beism \u02bfal\u0101 al-\u02beaxma\u1e63'')\n* 2019: ''Horse Cannon''  (\u0633\u0627\u0642 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0631\u0633 ''S\u0101q ul-faras'')\n\n=== Short Story Collections===\n* 2017: ''Widows' Garden'', (\u062d\u062f\u064a\u0642\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0631\u0627\u0645\u0644 ''\u1e24ad\u012bqat ul-\u02bear\u0101mil'')\n* 2017: ''What To Do Without Calvino?'', (\u0645\u0627\u0630\u0627 \u0646\u0641\u0639\u0644 \u0628\u062f\u0648\u0646 \u0643\u0627\u0644\u0641\u064a\u0646\u0648 ''M\u0101\u1e0f\u0101 naf\u02bfalu bid\u016bn k\u0101lf\u012bn\u016b'')\n* 2018: ''No Windmills in Basra'', (\u0644\u0627 \u0637\u0648\u0627\u062d\u064a\u0646 \u0647\u0648\u0627\u0621 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0635\u0631\u0629 ''L\u0101 \u1e6daw\u0101\u1e25\u012bn hawa\u02be f\u012bl-ba\u1e63ra'')\n\n=== Articles ===\n* 2018 Sep 13, \"Pollution and corruption are choking the life out of Basra\", ''The Guardian''\n* Diaa has other articles written in Arabic.\n\n=== English translations ===\n* {{cite book\n  | translator= Andrew Leber\n  | title     = ''\"The Worker\" in the short story anthology'' Iraq +100\n  | url       = https://commapress.co.uk/books/iraq-100\n  | date      = 17 November 2016\n  | publisher = Comma Press\n  | isbn      = 978-1-905-58366-9\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | translator= Alexander Hong\n  | title     = ''\"The Darwinist\", short story published in'' Strange Horizons\n  | url       = http://strangehorizons.com/fiction/the-darwinist-\u0627\u0644\u062f\u0627\u0631\u0648\u064a\u0646\u064a/\n  | date      = 30 October 2017\n  | publisher = Strange Horizons Magazine\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | translator= Yasmeen Hanoosh\n  | title     = The Cloven Man ''novel excerpt'' ''in'' Banipal'', issue #61''\n  | url       = https://www.banipal.co.uk/selections/99/339/%20dhia-jubaili/\n  | date      = 2018\n  | publisher = Banipal Magazine of Modern Arabic Literature\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | translator= Yasmeen Hanoosh\n  | title= ''\"The Scarecrow\" in the short story collection'' No Windmills in Basra\n  | url       = https://arablit.org/2019/04/13/on-209-submissions-for-2019-almultaqa-prize-for-the-arabic-short-story/\n  | date      = Spring 2019\n  | publisher = ArabLit Quarterly\n  }}\n\n==Awards and Honours==\n\n* 2007: {{flag|UAE}} Dubai Magazine Award for ''Curse of the Marquis''\n* 2017: {{flag|Sudan}} Tayeb Salih International Award for Creative Writing for the short story collection ''Widows' Garden'', ({{lang-ar|\u062c\u0627\u0626\u0632\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0637\u064a\u0628 \u0635\u0627\u0644\u062d \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0644\u0645\u064a\u0629 \u0644\u0625\u0628\u062f\u0627\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0643\u062a\u0627\u0628\u064a}})\n* 2018: {{flag|Kuwait}} Al Multaqa Prize for the Arabic Short Story for ''No Windmills in Basra'', ({{lang-ar|\u062c\u0627\u0626\u0632\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0644\u062a\u0642\u0649 \u0644\u0644\u0642\u0635\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0635\u064a\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629}})\n\nIn 2018, the short story collection ''No Windmills in Basra'' won the Al-Multaqa Prize for the Arabic short story.<ref>{{cite news|title='Diaa Jubaili Wins 2018 Almultaqa Prize for the Arabic Short Story'|url=https://arablit.org/2018/12/04/diaa-jubaili-wins-2018-almultaqa-prize-for-the-arabic-short-story/|accessdate=2 October 2019|publisher=ArabLit - Arabic Literature in Translation|date=4 December 2018}}</ref> This is a description from the report of the Al-Multaqa Prize Jury: \"The stories in Diaa Jubaili's collection vary in length from the very short to very long. They deal with the subjects of war by moving between reality and fantasy. With a sarcasm-laced narrative, he transforms the subject of war into a major introspective exercise on the significance of absurdity, nihilism, and a genuine desire to overcome the futility of death. The stories provide a reflection on the three wars of Iraq: the Iran-Iraq war, the 1991 Gulf War, and the 2003 American invasion, which set off a wave of extremism that is choking the country to this day.\"<ref>{{cite news|language=Arabic|title=\u0636\u064a\u0627\u0621 \u062c\u0628\u064a\u0644\u064a\u061b \u201c\u0644\u0627 \u0637\u0648\u0627\u062d\u064a\u0646 \u0647\u0648\u0627\u0621 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0635\u0631\u0629\u201d \u064a\u062d\u0635\u062f \u062c\u0627\u0626\u0632\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0644\u062a\u0642\u0649 \u0644\u0644\u0642\u0635\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0635\u064a\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629 \u0641\u064a \u062f\u0648\u0631\u0629 \u201c\u0625\u0633\u0645\u0627\u0639\u064a\u0644 \u0641\u0647\u062f \u0625\u0633\u0645\u0627\u0639\u064a\u0644\u201d 2017/2018|url=https://www.almultaqaprize.com/\u0636\u064a\u0627\u0621-\u062c\u0628\u064a\u0644\u064a\u061b-\u0644\u0627-\u0637\u0648\u0627\u062d\u064a\u0646-\u0647\u0648\u0627\u0621-\u0641\u064a-\u0627\u0644\u0628\u0635\u0631\u0629-\u064a/|accessdate=2 October 2019|institution=Al Multaqa Prize}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite news|title=Diaa Jubaili Wins 2018 Almultaqa Prize for the Arabic Short Story|url=https://arablit.org/2018/12/04/diaa-jubaili-wins-2018-almultaqa-prize-for-the-arabic-short-story/|work=Arab Lit|date=4 December 2018}}\n*{{cite news|title='Iraq + 100' Is Painful, But Don't Look Away|url=https://www.npr.org/2016/12/10/503068002/iraq-100-is-painful-but-dont-look-away?t=1570007487681|author=Amal El-Mohtar|newspaper=NPR News|date=10 December 2016}}\n*{{cite news|title=The Horror of the Iraq War, One Hundred Years From Now|url=https://theintercept.com/2017/01/15/the-horror-of-the-iraq-war-one-hundred-years-from-now/|author=Cora Currier|newspaper=The Intercept|date=15 January 2017}}\n*{{cite news|title=How Sci-Fi Writers Imagine Iraq\u2019s Future|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2017/10/how-sci-fi-writers-imagine-iraqs-future/541512/|accessdate=2 October 2019|magazine=The Atlantic|date=15 October 2017}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jubaili, Diaa}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Iraqi writers]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Iraqi novelists]]\n[[Category:Iraqi male short story writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{short description|Iraqi novelist}}\n{{Use British English Oxford spelling|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n|name         = Diaa Jubaili\n|image        = Diaa_Jubaili_Iraqi_Writer.jpg\n|imagesize    =\n|caption      = \n|birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1977|5|23}}\n|birth_place  = [[Basra]]\n|nationality  = {{flag|Iraq}}i\n|education    = \n|occupation   = Writer\n|notableworks = {{plainlist|\n*''No Windmills in Basra''\n*''What To Do Without Calvino?''\n*\"The Worker\" in ''Iraq + 100''\n*\"The Darwinist\" in ''Strange Horizons''}}\n\n|awards = \n*Al-Multaqa Prize for Arabic Short Fiction (2018)\n*Tayeb Salih International Award for Creative Writing (2017)\n*Dubai Culture Award (2007)\n}}\n\n'''Diaa Jubaili''' ({{lang-ar|\u0636\u064a\u0627\u0621 \u062c\u0628\u064a\u0644\u064a}}, (\u1e0c\u012bya Jubayl\u012b); born 23 May 1977) is an [[Iraqis|Iraqi]] novelist and writer from the city of Basra.\n\n==Biography==\nDiaa was born in [[Iraq]] in 1977 in the city of [[Basra]], where he is permanently based.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sci-fi stories envisage Iraq in 100 years|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-37687739|accessdate=2 October 2019|newspaper=BBC News|date=22 October 2016}}</ref> He became a writer and novelist in an environment which did not afford him a traditional education<ref>{{cite interview|last=Jubaili|first=Diaa|interviewer= Heather Sharp, BBC|work=Comma Press Blog|title=Iraq + 100: Diaa Jubaili on short stories and life in Basra (Part 1)|url=https://thecommapressblog.wordpress.com/2016/11/18/iraq-100-diaa-jubailie-on-short-stories-and-life-in-basra-part-1/|accessdate=2 October 2019|publisher=Comma Press|date=18 November 2016}}</ref> and also writes articles about life in Iraq.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pollution and corruption are choking the life out of Basra|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/sep/13/pollution-corruption-choking-life-out-of-basra|accessdate=2 October 2019|newspaper=The Guardian|date=13 September 2018}}</ref> An extensive reading of Western literature is an influence on his work.<ref>{{cite news|title='More story writers in Basra than even in Baghdad'|url=https://yourmiddleeast.com/2016/12/21/ae%CB%9Cmore-story-writers-in-basra-than-even-in-baghdad/|accessdate=2 October 2019|publisher=Your Middle East|date=21 December 2016}}</ref> In his fiction writing, he focuses on questions of identity in Iraq as well as the tension between religion and nationalism.<ref>{{cite news|language=Arabic|title=\u0631\u0648\u0627\u064a\u0629 \"\u0623\u0633\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0635\u0631\u0629\".. \u0639\u0646 \u0634\u062e\u0635\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0627\u0642 \u0627\u0644\u0636\u0627\u0626\u0639\u0629|url=https://www.aljazeera.net/news/cultureandart/2016/7/17/\u0631\u0648\u0627\u064a\u0629-\u0623\u0633\u062f-\u0627\u0644\u0628\u0635\u0631\u0629-\u0639\u0646-\u0634\u062e\u0635\u064a\u0629-\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0627\u0642-\u0627\u0644\u0636\u0627\u0626\u0639\u0629|accessdate=2 October 2019|newspaper=Al Jazeera|date=17 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nDiaa has won literary awards for his writing in Arabic. In 2017, he won the seventh annual Tayeb Salih International Award for Creative Writing for his novel ''What To Do Without Calvino?''.<ref>{{cite news|language=Arabic|title=\u0636\u064a\u0627\u0621 \u062c\u0628\u064a\u0644\u064a.. \u062c\u0627\u0626\u0632\u0629 \u0648\u062b\u0644\u0627\u062b\u0629 \u0643\u062a\u0628|url=https://www.ultrasawt.com/\u062b\u0642\u0627\u0641\u0629/\u0646\u0634\u0631\u0629-\u062b\u0642\u0627\u0641\u064a\u0629/\u0627\u0644\u062a\u0631\u0627-\u0635\u0648\u062a/\u0636\u064a\u0627\u0621-\u062c\u0628\u064a\u0644\u064a-\u062c\u0627\u0626\u0632\u0629-\u0648\u062b\u0644\u0627\u062b\u0629-\u0643\u062a\u0628|accessdate=2 October 2019|newspaper=Ultra Sawt|date=27 February 2017}}</ref> His  short story collection, ''No Windmills in Basra'', won the 2018 [[Al Multaqa Prize]] for the Arabic Short Story. The large prize purse of USD$20,000 is to encourage the short story genre in the Arab world.<ref>{{cite news|title=\nNew Arabic short story prize meets with cautious welcome|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/jan/01/new-arabic-short-story-prize-welcome-almutaqa|accessdate=2 October 2019|newspaper=The Guardian|date=1 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography in [[Arabic]]==\n\nDiaa has released eight novels and three short story collections in Arabic.\n\n=== Novels/Novellas ===\n* 2007: ''Curse of the Marquis''  (\u0644\u0639\u0646\u0629 \u0645\u0627\u0631\u0643\u064a\u0632 ''L\u02bfanat M\u0101rk\u012bz'')\n* 2009: ''The Ugly Face of Vincent'' (novella)  (\u0648\u062c\u0647 \u0641\u0646\u0633\u0646\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0628\u064a\u062d ''Wajh Finsint Alqab\u012b\u1e25'')\n* 2011: ''Bogeys, the Bizarre'' (novella)  (\u0628\u0648\u063a\u064a\u0632 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u062c\u064a\u0628 ''B\u016b\u0121\u012bz il-\u02bfaj\u012bb'')\n* 2014: ''General Stanley Maude's Souvenir''  (\u062a\u0630\u0643\u0627\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u062c\u0646\u0631\u0627\u0644 \u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646\u0644\u064a \u0645\u0648\u062f ''Ta\u1e0fk\u0101r il-jinr\u0101l sit\u0101nl\u012b mawd'')\n* 2016: ''The Lion of Basra''  (\u0623\u0633\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0635\u0631\u0629 ''\u02beasad il-ba\u1e63ra'')\n* 2017: ''The Cloven Man: Six Ways of Crossing Borders Illegally on the Way to Baghdad''  (\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0634\u0637\u0648\u0631, \u0633\u062a \u0637\u0631\u0627\u0626\u0642 \u063a\u064a\u0631 \u0634\u0631\u0639\u064a\u0629 \u0644\u0627\u062c\u062a\u064a\u0627\u0632 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u062f\u0648\u062f \u0646\u062d\u0648 \u0628\u063a\u062f\u0627\u062f ''Al-ma\u0161\u1e6d\u016br, sittu \u1e6dar\u0101\u02beiq \u0121ayr \u0161ar\u02bfiyya li\u02beitiyaz il-\u1e25ud\u016bd na\u1e25u ba\u0121d\u0101d'')\n* 2018: ''Name Upon the Hollow'', (\u0627\u0644\u0627\u0633\u0645 \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u062e\u0645\u0635 ''Al-\u02beism \u02bfal\u0101 al-\u02beaxma\u1e63'')\n* 2019: ''Horse Cannon''  (\u0633\u0627\u0642 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0631\u0633 ''S\u0101q ul-faras'')\n\n=== Short Story Collections===\n* 2017: ''Widows' Garden'', (\u062d\u062f\u064a\u0642\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0631\u0627\u0645\u0644 ''\u1e24ad\u012bqat ul-\u02bear\u0101mil'')\n* 2017: ''What To Do Without Calvino?'', (\u0645\u0627\u0630\u0627 \u0646\u0641\u0639\u0644 \u0628\u062f\u0648\u0646 \u0643\u0627\u0644\u0641\u064a\u0646\u0648 ''M\u0101\u1e0f\u0101 naf\u02bfalu bid\u016bn k\u0101lf\u012bn\u016b'')\n* 2018: ''No Windmills in Basra'', (\u0644\u0627 \u0637\u0648\u0627\u062d\u064a\u0646 \u0647\u0648\u0627\u0621 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0635\u0631\u0629 ''L\u0101 \u1e6daw\u0101\u1e25\u012bn hawa\u02be f\u012bl-ba\u1e63ra'')\n\n=== Articles ===\n* 2018 Sep 13, \"Pollution and corruption are choking the life out of Basra\", ''The Guardian''\n* Diaa has other articles written in Arabic.\n\n=== English translations ===\n* {{cite book\n  | translator= Andrew Leber\n  | title     = ''\"The Worker\" in the short story anthology'' Iraq +100\n  | url       = https://commapress.co.uk/books/iraq-100\n  | date      = 17 November 2016\n  | publisher = Comma Press\n  | isbn      = 978-1-905-58366-9\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | translator= Alexander Hong\n  | title     = ''\"The Darwinist\", short story published in'' Strange Horizons\n  | url       = http://strangehorizons.com/fiction/the-darwinist-\u0627\u0644\u062f\u0627\u0631\u0648\u064a\u0646\u064a/\n  | date      = 30 October 2017\n  | publisher = Strange Horizons Magazine\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | translator= Yasmeen Hanoosh\n  | title     = The Cloven Man ''novel excerpt'' ''in'' Banipal'', issue #61''\n  | url       = https://www.banipal.co.uk/selections/99/339/%20dhia-jubaili/\n  | date      = 2018\n  | publisher = Banipal Magazine of Modern Arabic Literature\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | translator= Yasmeen Hanoosh\n  | title= ''\"The Scarecrow\" in the short story collection'' No Windmills in Basra\n  | url       = https://arablit.org/2019/04/13/on-209-submissions-for-2019-almultaqa-prize-for-the-arabic-short-story/\n  | date      = Spring 2019\n  | publisher = ArabLit Quarterly\n  }}\n\n==Awards and Honours==\n\n* 2007: {{flag|UAE}} Dubai Magazine Award for ''Curse of the Marquis''\n* 2017: {{flag|Sudan}} Tayeb Salih International Award for Creative Writing for the short story collection ''Widows' Garden'', ({{lang-ar|\u062c\u0627\u0626\u0632\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0637\u064a\u0628 \u0635\u0627\u0644\u062d \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0644\u0645\u064a\u0629 \u0644\u0625\u0628\u062f\u0627\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0643\u062a\u0627\u0628\u064a}})\n* 2018: {{flag|Kuwait}} Al Multaqa Prize for the Arabic Short Story for ''No Windmills in Basra'', ({{lang-ar|\u062c\u0627\u0626\u0632\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0644\u062a\u0642\u0649 \u0644\u0644\u0642\u0635\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0635\u064a\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629}})\n\nIn 2018, the short story collection ''No Windmills in Basra'' won the Al-Multaqa Prize for the Arabic short story.<ref>{{cite news|title='Diaa Jubaili Wins 2018 Almultaqa Prize for the Arabic Short Story'|url=https://arablit.org/2018/12/04/diaa-jubaili-wins-2018-almultaqa-prize-for-the-arabic-short-story/|accessdate=2 October 2019|publisher=ArabLit - Arabic Literature in Translation|date=4 December 2018}}</ref> This is a description from the report of the Al-Multaqa Prize Jury: \"The stories in Diaa Jubaili's collection vary in length from the very short to very long. They deal with the subjects of war by moving between reality and fantasy. With a sarcasm-laced narrative, he transforms the subject of war into a major introspective exercise on the significance of absurdity, nihilism, and a genuine desire to overcome the futility of death. The stories provide a reflection on the three wars of Iraq: the Iran-Iraq war, the 1991 Gulf War, and the 2003 American invasion, which set off a wave of extremism that is choking the country to this day.\"<ref>{{cite news|language=Arabic|title=\u0636\u064a\u0627\u0621 \u062c\u0628\u064a\u0644\u064a\u061b \u201c\u0644\u0627 \u0637\u0648\u0627\u062d\u064a\u0646 \u0647\u0648\u0627\u0621 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0635\u0631\u0629\u201d \u064a\u062d\u0635\u062f \u062c\u0627\u0626\u0632\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0644\u062a\u0642\u0649 \u0644\u0644\u0642\u0635\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0635\u064a\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629 \u0641\u064a \u062f\u0648\u0631\u0629 \u201c\u0625\u0633\u0645\u0627\u0639\u064a\u0644 \u0641\u0647\u062f \u0625\u0633\u0645\u0627\u0639\u064a\u0644\u201d 2017/2018|url=https://www.almultaqaprize.com/\u0636\u064a\u0627\u0621-\u062c\u0628\u064a\u0644\u064a\u061b-\u0644\u0627-\u0637\u0648\u0627\u062d\u064a\u0646-\u0647\u0648\u0627\u0621-\u0641\u064a-\u0627\u0644\u0628\u0635\u0631\u0629-\u064a/|accessdate=2 October 2019|institution=Al Multaqa Prize}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite news|title=Diaa Jubaili Wins 2018 Almultaqa Prize for the Arabic Short Story|url=https://arablit.org/2018/12/04/diaa-jubaili-wins-2018-almultaqa-prize-for-the-arabic-short-story/|work=Arab Lit|date=4 December 2018}}\n*{{cite news|title='Iraq + 100' Is Painful, But Don't Look Away|url=https://www.npr.org/2016/12/10/503068002/iraq-100-is-painful-but-dont-look-away