{"title_page": "Motets by Johann Sebastian Bach, discography", "text_new": "This article includes a list of commercial recordings of the [[Motet (Bach)|motets]] of [[Johann Sebastian Bach]]. Bach motets have often been recorded as a set (typically comprising the six motets catalogued as BWV{{nbsp}}225-230).{{efn|\"BWV\" is [[Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis]], a thematic catalogue of Bach's works.}}  However, other motets are attributed to Bach and there is some doubt about the authorship of [[Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden, BWV 230|''Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden'', BWV 230]], one of the {{abbr|BWV|Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis (catalogue of Bach's works)}} \"six\".\n\nA single CD can contain the set of six motets plus other works. For example, [[Maasaki Suzuki]]'s 2009 recording on [[BIS Records|BIS]] includes [[O Jesu Christ, meins Lebens Licht, BWV 118|''O Jesu Christ, meins Lebens Licht'', BWV 118]] (which at one time was categorised as a cantata) and [[Ich lasse dich nicht, BWV Anh. 159|''Ich lasse dich nicht'', BWV Anh. 159]] (the authorship of which has been disputed).<ref name=\"BIS\">{{Cite web |url=https://bis.se/conductors/suzuki-masaaki/bach-motets |title=Bach Motets |website=bis.se (BIS Records) |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> The motets chosen for a particular recording can reflect the way the balance of opinion changes regarding the status of a particular work. This appears to be the case with the two sets by [[John Eliot Gardiner]] conducting the [[Monteverdi Choir]]. They recorded Bach's motets without {{nowrap|BWV Anh. 159}} in 1980, but included it in their 2011 live recording.<ref name=\"muzie\">[https://www.muziekweb.nl/en/Link/DBX11558 ''Bach: Motets''] and [https://www.muziekweb.nl/en/Link/DBX10438 ''Bach Motets''] at {{url|www.muziekweb.nl}}.</ref>\n\n== Types of choirs ==\nChoirs with [[one voice per part]] (OVPP) are used in some [[historically informed performance]]s of Bach. However, OVPP recordings of the motets are relatively rare. Exceptions include the [[Hilliard Ensemble]]'s second set,<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{Cite news |last=Clements |first=Andrew |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2007/may/18/classicalmusicandopera.shopping2 |title=Bach: Motets |date=18 May 2007 |work=The Guardian}}</ref> and [[Konrad Jungh\u00e4nel]] with the group Cantus C\u00f6lln.<ref name=\"Bach Cantatas6\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec6.htm |title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 6 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref>\n\nAt least some of the motets would have been first performed by singers from Leipzig's [[Thomanerchor]]. This choir has recorded the motets (initially under [[G\u00fcnther Ramin]] in the 1950s),<ref name=\"Bach Cantatas2\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec2.htm  |title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 2 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref> as have other choirs with boys voices such as the [[Choir of New College, Oxford]]\n\n== Instrumental accompaniment ==\nMusic directors need to make choices about the instrumental accompaniment, if any, to be used. One approach is to have instruments doubling the vocal lines, something which is described as playing ''[[colla parte]]''.\nSurviving sources do not make it clear what Bach's approach was to the accompaniment of most of these pieces. In the case of [[Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf, BWV 226|''Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf'', BWV 226]] orchestral parts are extant, indicating that choir I was doubled by strings and choir II by reeds (two [[oboe]]s, [[Taille (instrument)|taille]] and [[bassoon]]). There is also a [[basso continuo]] (separate [[violone]] and [[Organ (music)|organ]] parts are provided) which underlies both choirs.<ref name=\"bachchoir\">{{Cite web |url=https://bach.org/education/motet-bwv-226/ |title=Motet BWV 226 |website=Bach Choir of Bethlehem |access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\nAn accompaniment is also specified for ''Lobet den Herrn''.<ref name=\"Leavis\">{{cite web | url= https://www.jstor.org/stable/731829| title=Bach's Setting of Psalm CXVII (BWV.230) | publisher=OUP | work=[[Music & Letters]]. Vol. 52, No. 1 | date=January 1971 | author=Leavis, Ralph}}  Accessed via JSTOR (subscription required)</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe first of the motets to be recorded was [[Jesu, meine Freude, BWV 227|''Jesu meine Freude'']] in 1927. This version was sung in English.<ref name=\"Bach Cantatas1\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec1.htm|title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 1 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nIn 2010, Suzuki and his ensemble were given a French award ([[Diapason d'Or|Diapason d\u2019Or de l\u2019Ann\u00e9e]]) and a German award ([[Preis der deutschen Schallplattenkritik]]) for their recording of Bach motets on BIS.\n \nJohn Eliot Gardiner, who has won more [[Gramophone Classical Music Awards|Gramophone Awards]] than any other living artist, received one for his second recording of the motets with the Monteverdi Choir on SDG. It was one of the [[Gramophone_Classical_Music_Awards#2013|2013 awards]], the category being \"Baroque Vocal\".\n\nGrete Pedersen with the Norwegian choir [[Det Norske Solistkor]] won a Diapason d'Or in 2018 for their recording of the motets on BIS.\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Cantata discography header |work= Bach Motets |show_more=yes |more = Additional info}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Ramin\n| title = \n| conductor = {{sortname|G\u00fcnther|Ramin}}\n| choir = [[Thomanerchor]]\n| instrumentalists =\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = [[Archiv]] (reissue)\n| year = 1950s\n| more =\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Christophers\n| title = The Six Motets<ref name=\"BachCantatas5\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec5.htm|title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 5 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref>\n| conductor = {{sortname|Harry|Christophers}}\n| choir = [[The Sixteen]]\n| instrumentalists =\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = [[Hyperion Records|Hyperion]]\n| year = 1989\n| more =\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = \n| title = Bach Motetten\n| conductor = \n| choir = [[Hilliard Ensemble]]\n| instrumentalists =\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = [[ECM Records|ECM]]\n| year = 2003\n| more = second Hilliard recording\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Higginbottom\n| title = Bach Motets<ref name=\"BachCantatas7\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec7.htm|title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 7 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref>\n| conductor = [[Edward Higginbottom]]\n| choir = [[Choir of New College, Oxford]]\n| instrumentalists = organ\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = Novum<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.newcollegechoir.com/news/?pid=7&nid=1&storyid=12 |title=Recordings |website=Choir of New College, Oxford}}</ref>\n| year = 2008\n| more = organ accompaniment\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Suzuki\n| title = Bach Motets<ref name=\"BIS\"></ref>\n| conductor = {{sortname|Masaaki|Suzuki}}\n| choir = [[Bach Collegium Japan]]\n| instrumentalists =\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = [[BIS Records|BIS]]\n| year = 2009\n| more =\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Gardiner2\n| title =Bach Motets<ref name=\"muzie\"></ref>\n| conductor = {{sortname|John Eliot|Gardiner}}\n| choir = [[Monteverdi Choir]]\n| instrumentalists =\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = [[Soli Deo Gloria (record label)|SDG]]\n| year = 2011\n| more = second Gardiner recording\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Pedersen\n| title =\n| conductor = {{sortname|Grete|Pedersen}}\n| choir = [[Det Norske Solistkor|Norwegian Soloists' Choir]]\n| instrumentalists = Ensemble Allegria\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = BIS\n| year = 2017\n| more = \n}}\n{{End}}\n{{expand list|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Discographies of compositions by J. S. Bach]]\n", "text_old": "This article includes a list of commercial recordings of the [[Motet (Bach)|motets]] of [[Johann Sebastian Bach]]. Bach motets have often been recorded as a set (typically comprising the six motets catalogued as BWV{{nbsp}}225-230).{{efn|\"BWV\" is [[Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis]], a thematic catalogue of Bach's works.}}  However, other motets are attributed to Bach and there is some doubt about the authorship of [[Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden, BWV 230|''Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden'', BWV 230]], one of the {{abbr|BWV|Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis (catalogue of Bach's works)}} \"six\".\n\nA single CD can contain the set of six motets plus other works. For example, [[Maasaki Suzuki]]'s 2009 recording on [[BIS Records|BIS]] includes [[O Jesu Christ, meins Lebens Licht, BWV 118|''O Jesu Christ, meins Lebens Licht'', BWV 118]] (which at one time was categorised as a cantata) and [[Ich lasse dich nicht, BWV Anh. 159|''Ich lasse dich nicht'', BWV Anh. 159]] (the authorship of which has been disputed).<ref name=\"BIS\">{{Cite web |url=https://bis.se/conductors/suzuki-masaaki/bach-motets |title=Bach Motets |website=bis.se (BIS Records) |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> The motets chosen for a particular recording can reflect the way the balance of opinion changes regarding the status of a particular work. This appears to be the case with the two sets by [[John Eliot Gardiner]] conducting the [[Monteverdi Choir]]. They recorded Bach's motets without {{nowrap|BWV Anh. 159}} in 1980, but included it in their 2011 live recording.<ref name=\"muzie\">[https://www.muziekweb.nl/en/Link/DBX11558 ''Bach: Motets''] and [https://www.muziekweb.nl/en/Link/DBX10438 ''Bach Motets''] at {{url|www.muziekweb.nl}}.</ref>\n\n== Types of choirs ==\nChoirs with [[one voice per part]] (OVPP) are used in some historically informed performances of Bach. However, OVPP recordings of the motets are relatively rare. Exceptions include the [[Hilliard Ensemble]]'s second set,<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{Cite news |last=Clements |first=Andrew |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2007/may/18/classicalmusicandopera.shopping2 |title=Bach: Motets |date=18 May 2007 |work=The Guardian}}</ref> and [[Konrad Jungh\u00e4nel]] with the group Cantus C\u00f6lln.<ref name=\"Bach Cantatas6\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec6.htm |title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 6 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref>\n\nAt least some of the motets would have been first performed by singers from Leipzig's [[Thomanerchor]]. This choir has recorded the motets (initially under [[G\u00fcnther Ramin]] in the 1950s),<ref name=\"Bach Cantatas2\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec2.htm  |title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 2 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref> as have other choirs with boys voices such as the [[Choir of New College, Oxford]]\n\n== Instrumental accompaniment ==\nMusic directors need to make choices about the instrumental accompaniment, if any, to be used. One approach is to have instruments doubling the vocal lines, something which is described as playing ''[[colla parte]]''.\nSurviving sources do not make it clear what Bach's approach was to the accompaniment of most of these pieces. In the case of [[Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf, BWV 226|''Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf'', BWV 226]] orchestral parts are extant, indicating that choir I was doubled by strings and choir II by reeds (two [[oboe]]s, [[Taille (instrument)|taille]] and [[bassoon]]). There is also a [[basso continuo]] (separate [[violone]] and [[Organ (music)|organ]] parts are provided) which underlies both choirs.<ref name=\"bachchoir\">{{Cite web |url=https://bach.org/education/motet-bwv-226/ |title=Motet BWV 226 |website=Bach Choir of Bethlehem |access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\nAn accompaniment is also specified for ''Lobet den Herrn''.<ref name=\"Leavis\">{{cite web | url= https://www.jstor.org/stable/731829| title=Bach's Setting of Psalm CXVII (BWV.230) | publisher=OUP | work=[[Music & Letters]]. Vol. 52, No. 1 | date=January 1971 | author=Leavis, Ralph}}  Accessed via JSTOR (subscription required)</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe first of the motets to be recorded was [[Jesu, meine Freude, BWV 227|''Jesu meine Freude'']] in 1927. This version was sung in English.<ref name=\"Bach Cantatas1\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec1.htm|title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 1 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nIn 2010, Suzuki and his ensemble were given a French award ([[Diapason d'Or|Diapason d\u2019Or de l\u2019Ann\u00e9e]]) and a German award ([[Preis der deutschen Schallplattenkritik]]) for their recording of Bach motets on BIS.\n \nJohn Eliot Gardiner, who has won more [[Gramophone Classical Music Awards|Gramophone Awards]] than any other living artist, received one for his second recording of the motets with the Monteverdi Choir on SDG. It was one of the [[Gramophone_Classical_Music_Awards#2013|2013 awards]], the category being \"Baroque Vocal\".\n\nGrete Pedersen with the Norwegian choir [[Det Norske Solistkor]] won a Diapason d'Or in 2018 for their recording of the motets on BIS.\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Cantata discography header |work= Bach Motets |show_more=yes |more = Additional info}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Ramin\n| title = \n| conductor = {{sortname|G\u00fcnther|Ramin}}\n| choir = [[Thomanerchor]]\n| instrumentalists =\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = [[Archiv]] (reissue)\n| year = 1950s\n| more =\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Christophers\n| title = The Six Motets<ref name=\"BachCantatas5\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec5.htm|title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 5 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref>\n| conductor = {{sortname|Harry|Christophers}}\n| choir = [[The Sixteen]]\n| instrumentalists =\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = [[Hyperion Records|Hyperion]]\n| year = 1989\n| more =\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = \n| title = Bach Motetten\n| conductor = \n| choir = [[Hilliard Ensemble]]\n| instrumentalists =\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = [[ECM Records|ECM]]\n| year = 2003\n| more = second Hilliard recording\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Higginbottom\n| title = Bach Motets<ref name=\"BachCantatas7\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec7.htm|title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 7 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref>\n| conductor = [[Edward Higginbottom]]\n| choir = [[Choir of New College, Oxford]]\n| instrumentalists = organ\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = Novum<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.newcollegechoir.com/news/?pid=7&nid=1&storyid=12 |title=Recordings |website=Choir of New College, Oxford}}</ref>\n| year = 2008\n| more = organ accompaniment\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Suzuki\n| title = Bach Motets<ref name=\"BIS\"></ref>\n| conductor = {{sortname|Masaaki|Suzuki}}\n| choir = [[Bach Collegium Japan]]\n| instrumentalists =\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = [[BIS Records|BIS]]\n| year = 2009\n| more =\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Gardiner2\n| title =Bach Motets<ref name=\"muzie\"></ref>\n| conductor = {{sortname|John Eliot|Gardiner}}\n| choir = [[Monteverdi Choir]]\n| instrumentalists =\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = [[Soli Deo Gloria (record label)|SDG]]\n| year = 2011\n| more = second Gardiner recording\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Pedersen\n| title =\n| conductor = {{sortname|Grete|Pedersen}}\n| choir = [[Det Norske Solistkor|Norwegian Soloists' Choir]]\n| instrumentalists = Ensemble Allegria\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = BIS\n| year = 2017\n| more = \n}}\n{{End}}\n{{expand list|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Discographies of compositions by J. S. Bach]]\n", "name_user": "Thoughtfortheday", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTypes of choirs:wl", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Motets_by_Johann_Sebastian_Bach,_discography"}
{"title_page": "Dheeraj Verma", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Dheeraj Verma\n| image =Dheeraj verma.jpg\n| image_size = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1967|10|22|df=y}}\n| birth_place = New Delhi, India\n| nationality = Indian\n| occupation = writer, artist, penciller, painter, digital painter, martial artist\n}}\n'''Dheeraj Verma''' (born 22 October 1967) is an internationally renowned Indian comic book artist/creator. Verma is often credited with being the first Indian to enter the US comics industry.\n\n== Early life ==\n\nDheeraj Verma was born on 22 October 1967 in [[Delhi]], [[India]]. He attended school at N P Boys Sr Secondary School and graduated from [[Pannalal Girdharlal Dayanand Anglo Vedic College]], [[University of Delhi]] in 1991. Dheeraj spent his life in the heart of the capital, Connaught Place. As an aspiring artist he started drawing \"The Phantom, Batman and Superman\" in his 3rd grade. He was quite impressed with \"The Phantom and Flash Gordon\" which became his inspiration to draw.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\n== Career ==\nVerma started his career as an illustrator in the Indian comic industry in 1991 with the New Delhi-based publishers Parampara Comics and Fort Comics. He was noticed by the industry with ''Divaystro Ka Raja'', ''Ajoobey'' ( Parampara Comics) and garnered more attention from the Indian comics industry with the comics  ''Jangaroo'' (Fort Comics). {{citation needed|date=January 2017}} Later, in December 1993, he moved on to [[Raj Comics]], the leading Indian comic company of the time. There he created his famous one-of-a-kind wolfman character [[Bheriya]]. Bheriya (wolfman) represents Verma\u2019s immense love and dedication towards wild life and nature, which have always been the strongest aspects of his lifestyle. His debut issue in Raj Comics was ''Bheria Aya'' in 1994. He also wrote as well as illustrated its initial issues which were a huge hit such as ''Wolfano'', ''Grahano'', ''Lazy'', ''Tilangey'' and many more. He worked on almost all the major Raj comics characters as an artist.<ref name=\"avatarpress.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.avatarpress.com/people/dheeraj-verma|title=People - Dheeraj Verma - Avatar Press|publisher=}}</ref> His best selling comics were from the 90\u2019s, and all of them were drawn by him. He also worked on covers, posters, trading cards, pin-ups, and other promotional merchandising for Raj comics. Verma was the first artist to introduce digital coloring to the Indian comic industry in 1996 on ''Parmanu''{{'}}s cover and then ''Bheria\u2019s Digest''.<ref name=\"avatarpress.com\"/> He worked with Raj comics until April 2000. He joined a gaming company Escosoft Tech. (Division of Escort) as a senior visualizer and worked there for three years until June 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escosoft-tech.com/|title=escosoft-tech.com|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, he got his big break in the American comic industry with [[Avatar Press]] where he worked as an artist for writer [[Joe R. Lansdale]] on ''By Bizarre Hands''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avatarpress.com/bybizarrehands/|title=Joe R. Lansdale's By Bizarre Hands -- Avatar Press|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joerlansdale.com/bio.html|title=Joe R. Lansdale, A Biography & Bibliography|publisher=}}</ref> His biggest series with Avatar was ''[[Escape of the Living Dead]]'' ,<ref>http://www.avatarpress.com/escape/</ref> ''Plague of the Living Dead'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avatarpress.com/tag/plague-of-the-living-dead/|title=plague of the living dead - Avatar Press|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comixology.com/Plague-of-the-Living-Dead-1-of-6/digital-comic/50546|title=Plague of the Living Dead #1 (of 6) - Comics by comiXology|publisher=}}</ref> ''[[Yuggoth Creatures]]'',<ref>http://www.avatarpress.com/yuggothcreatures/</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.antonyjohnston.com/work/yuggothcreatures/|title=Antony Johnston|publisher=}}</ref> ''Nightmare on Elm Street,''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avatarpress.com/nightmare/|title=Avatar Press|publisher=}}</ref> and ''Night of the Living Dead''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avatarpress.com/tag/night-of-the-living-dead/|title=night of the living dead - Avatar Press|publisher=}}</ref> He also worked on Dynamite\u2019s ''The Complete Dracula'' series written by Alan Moore\u2019s daughter [[Leah Moore]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dynamite.com/htmlfiles/viewProduct.html?PRO=C725130117915|title=Dynamite\u00ae The Complete Dracula #1 (Of 5)|publisher=}}</ref> He also did cover art for [[Marvel Comics]]'s invincible [[Iron Man]] .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://marvel.com/comics/creators/10283/dheeraj_verma|title=Dheeraj Verma - Comics - Marvel.com|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://marvel.com/comics/list/10283/crdSeriesByCreator/dheeraj_verma|title=Dheeraj Verma - Comics - Marvel.com|publisher=}}</ref> He worked on [[Transformers]]' series published by [[IDW Publications]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.idwpublishing.com/product-tag/dheeraj-verma/|title=Dheeraj Verma|work=IDW Publishing}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tfwiki.net/wiki/Dheeraj_Verma|title=Dheeraj Verma|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idwpublishing.com/transformers/|title=Transformers|work=IDW Publishing}}</ref> His first series for IDW ''Transforemers: Fall Of Cybertron'' was a superhit series on [[ComiXology]], which was  launched in Aug 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comixology.com/Transformers-Fall-of-Cybertron/comics-series/8674|title=Transformers: Fall of Cybertron|publisher=}}</ref> After this series he worked on ''Transformers: Robots in Disguise'' # 19. In July 2013 and it entered in Top 300 comics. 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://icv2.com/articles/comics/view/26456/top-300-comics-actual-july-2013|title=ICv2: Top 300 Comics Actual--July 2013|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nHe has done up to 14 issues of Lady Death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://coffincomics.com/tag/lady-death/|title=lady death \u00bb Coffin Comics|work=Coffin Comics}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/brianpulido/bpulidos-new-lady-death-graphic-novel-extinction-e|title=B.PULIDO\u2019S NEW LADY DEATH GRAPHIC NOVEL: EXTINCTION EXPRESS!|work=Kickstarter}}</ref>\n\nHe is currently working on [[Conan the Slayer]] ( Dark Horse comics, USA), as a penciller.\n\nIn January 2013, after a decade away, Verma made his comeback in the Indian comic industry with ''Jaljeevni'' (Bheria Series) from Raj Comics. ''Subhasya Sheegram'' ([[Doga (comics)|Doga]]), Sarvanayak series is his latest on-going project with Raj Comics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rajcomics.com/index.php/12566/1006/bestsellers/bestsellers-last-6-month/sarvyugam-detail|title=Last 6 Month : SARVYUGAM|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rajcomics.com/index.php/12582/1006/bestsellers/bestsellers-last-6-month/sarvdaman-detail|title=Last 6 Month : SARVDAMAN|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nVerma also ventured to exhibit his painting in the world renowned Indian Government national academy of fine arts [[Lalit Kala Akademi]] in Delhi, and caused quite a buzz in the fine art circle by introducing original comics pages from Transformers and Lady Death in the gallery in a seven-day exhibition, which was Inaugurated by Mr. Taj Hassan, Special Commissioner of Police.<ref>http://lalitkala.gov.in/upload/Gallery%20Allotment%20list.pdf</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delhievents.com/2015/10/artist-dheeraj-verma-presents-strong.html|title=Delhi Events|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nVerma married Malti Verma in 1991 and has two daughters.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.culturepopcorn.com/interviews/exclusive-interview-with-dheeraj-verma-transformers-batman/ Exclusive Interview with Dheeraj Verma : Transformers to Batman]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Verma, Dheeraj}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Artists from Delhi]]\n[[Category:Indian graphic novelists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Dheeraj Verma\n| image =Dheeraj verma.jpg\n| image_size = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1967|10|22|df=y}}\n| birth_place = New Delhi, India\n| nationality = Indian\n| occupation = writer, artist, penciller, painter, digital painter, martial artist\n}}\n'''Dheeraj Verma''' (born 22 October 1967) is an internationally renowned Indian comic book artist/creator. Verma is often credited with being the first Indian to enter the US comics industry.\n\n== Early life ==\n\nDheeraj Verma was born on 22 October 1967 in [[Delhi]], [[India]]. He attended school at N P Boys Sr Secondary School and graduated from [[Pannalal Girdharlal Dayanand Anglo Vedic College]], [[University of Delhi]] in 1991. Dheeraj spent his life in the heart of the capital, Connaught Place. As an aspiring artist he started drawing \"The Phantom, Batman and Superman\" in his 3rd grade. He was quite impressed with \"The Phantom and Flash Gordon\" which became his inspiration to draw.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\n== Career ==\nVerma started his career as an illustrator in the Indian comic industry in 1991 with the New Delhi-based publishers Parampara Comics and Fort Comics. He was noticed by the industry with ''Divaystro Ka Raja'', ''Ajoobey'' ( Parampara Comics) and garnered more attention from the Indian comics industry with the comics  ''Jangaroo'' (Fort Comics). {{citation needed|date=January 2017}} Later, in December 1993, he moved on to [[Raj Comics]], the leading Indian comic company of the time. There he created his famous one-of-a-kind wolfman character [[Bheriya]]. Bheriya (wolfman) represents Verma\u2019s immense love and dedication towards wild life and nature, which have always been the strongest aspects of his lifestyle. His debut issue in Raj Comics was ''Bheria Aya'' in 1994. He also wrote as well as illustrated its initial issues which were a huge hit such as ''Wolfano'', ''Grahano'', ''Lazy'', ''Tilangey'' and many more. He worked on almost all the major Raj comics characters as an artist.<ref name=\"avatarpress.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.avatarpress.com/people/dheeraj-verma|title=People - Dheeraj Verma - Avatar Press|publisher=}}</ref> His best selling comics were from the 90\u2019s, and all of them were drawn by him. He also worked on covers, posters, trading cards, pin-ups, and other promotional merchandising for Raj comics. Verma was the first artist to introduce digital coloring to the Indian comic industry in 1996 on ''Parmanu''{{'}}s cover and then ''Bheria\u2019s Digest''.<ref name=\"avatarpress.com\"/> He worked with Raj comics until April 2000. He joined a gaming company Escosoft Tech. (Division of Escort) as a senior visualizer and worked there for three years until June 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escosoft-tech.com/|title=escosoft-tech.com|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, he got his big break in the American comic industry with [[Avatar Press]] where he worked as an artist for writer [[Joe R. Lansdale]] on ''By Bizarre Hands''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avatarpress.com/bybizarrehands/|title=Joe R. Lansdale's By Bizarre Hands -- Avatar Press|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joerlansdale.com/bio.html|title=Joe R. Lansdale, A Biography & Bibliography|publisher=}}</ref> His biggest series with Avatar was ''[[Escape of the Living Dead]]'' ,<ref>http://www.avatarpress.com/escape/</ref> ''Plague of the Living Dead'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avatarpress.com/tag/plague-of-the-living-dead/|title=plague of the living dead - Avatar Press|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comixology.com/Plague-of-the-Living-Dead-1-of-6/digital-comic/50546|title=Plague of the Living Dead #1 (of 6) - Comics by comiXology|publisher=}}</ref> ''[[Yuggoth Creatures]]'',<ref>http://www.avatarpress.com/yuggothcreatures/</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.antonyjohnston.com/work/yuggothcreatures/|title=Antony Johnston|publisher=}}</ref> ''Nightmare on Elm Street,''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avatarpress.com/nightmare/|title=Avatar Press|publisher=}}</ref> and ''Night of the Living Dead''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avatarpress.com/tag/night-of-the-living-dead/|title=night of the living dead - Avatar Press|publisher=}}</ref> He also worked on Dynamite\u2019s ''The Complete Dracula'' series written by Alan Moore\u2019s daughter [[Leah Moore]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dynamite.com/htmlfiles/viewProduct.html?PRO=C725130117915|title=Dynamite\u00ae The Complete Dracula #1 (Of 5)|publisher=}}</ref> He also did cover art for [[Marvel Comics]]'s invincible [[Iron Man]] .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://marvel.com/comics/creators/10283/dheeraj_verma|title=Dheeraj Verma - Comics - Marvel.com|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://marvel.com/comics/list/10283/crdSeriesByCreator/dheeraj_verma|title=Dheeraj Verma - Comics - Marvel.com|publisher=}}</ref> He worked on [[Transformers]]' series published by [[IDW Publications]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.idwpublishing.com/product-tag/dheeraj-verma/|title=Dheeraj Verma|work=IDW Publishing}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tfwiki.net/wiki/Dheeraj_Verma|title=Dheeraj Verma|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idwpublishing.com/transformers/|title=Transformers|work=IDW Publishing}}</ref> His first series for IDW ''Transforemers: Fall Of Cybertron'' was a superhit series on [[ComiXology]], which was  launched in Aug 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comixology.com/Transformers-Fall-of-Cybertron/comics-series/8674|title=Transformers: Fall of Cybertron|publisher=}}</ref> After this series he worked on ''Transformers: Robots in Disguise'' # 19. In July 2013 and it entered in Top 300 comics. 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://icv2.com/articles/comics/view/26456/top-300-comics-actual-july-2013|title=ICv2: Top 300 Comics Actual--July 2013|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nHe has done up to 14 issues of Lady Death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://coffincomics.com/tag/lady-death/|title=lady death \u00bb Coffin Comics|work=Coffin Comics}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/brianpulido/bpulidos-new-lady-death-graphic-novel-extinction-e|title=B.PULIDO\u2019S NEW LADY DEATH GRAPHIC NOVEL: EXTINCTION EXPRESS!|work=Kickstarter}}</ref>\n\nHe is currently working on [[Conan the Slayer]] ( Dark Horse comics, USA), as a penciller.\n\nIn January 2013, after a decade away, Verma made his comeback in the Indian comic industry with ''Jaljeevni'' (Bheria Series) from Raj Comics. ''Subhasya Sheegram'' ([[Doga (comics)|Doga]]), Sarvanayak series is his latest on-going project with Raj Comics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rajcomics.com/index.php/12566/1006/bestsellers/bestsellers-last-6-month/sarvyugam-detail|title=Last 6 Month : SARVYUGAM|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rajcomics.com/index.php/12582/1006/bestsellers/bestsellers-last-6-month/sarvdaman-detail|title=Last 6 Month : SARVDAMAN|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nVerma also ventured to exhibit his painting in the world renowned Indian Government national academy of fine arts [[Lalit Kala Akademi]] in Delhi, and caused quite a buzz in the fine art circle by introducing original comics pages from Transformers and Lady Death in the gallery in a seven-day exhibition, which was Inaugurated by Mr. Taj Hassan, Special Commissioner of Police.<ref>http://lalitkala.gov.in/upload/Gallery%20Allotment%20list.pdf</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delhievents.com/2015/10/artist-dheeraj-verma-presents-strong.html|title=Delhi Events|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nVerma married Malti Verma in 1991 and has two daughters.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.culturepopcorn.com/interviews/exclusive-interview-with-dheeraj-verma-transformers-batman/ Exclusive Interview with Dheeraj Verma : Transformers to Batman]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Verma, Dheeraj}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Artists from Delhi]]\n[[Category:Indian graphic novelists]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dheeraj_Verma"}
{"title_page": "Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's Greco-Roman 84 kg", "text_new": "{{Infobox Olympic event\n|event = Men's Greco-Roman 84 kg\n|games = 2012 Summer \n|image = Medalists at the Men's 84 kg Greco Roman Wrestling.jpg\n|image_size = 150px\n|caption =\n|venue = [[ExCeL Exhibition Centre]]\n|date = 6 August\n|competitors = 20\n|nations = 20\n|gold        = [[Alan Khugaev]]\n|goldNOC     =RUS\n|silver      = [[Karam Gaber]]\n|silverNOC   =EGY\n|bronze      = [[Daniyal Gadzhiyev]]\n|bronzeNOC   =KAZ\n|bronze2     = [[Damian Janikowski]]\n|bronzeNOC2  =POL\n|prev = [[Wrestling at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's Greco-Roman 84 kg|2008]]\n|next = [[Wrestling at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's Greco-Roman 85 kg|2016]]\n}}\n\n{{WrestlingAt2012SummerOlympics}}\n'''Men's Greco-Roman 84&nbsp;kg''' competition at the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] in [[London]], [[United Kingdom]], took place on 6 August at [[ExCeL London]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london2012.com/wrestling/event/men-greco-roman-84kg/index.html|title=Men's 84kg Greco-Roman|work=london2012.com|accessdate=18 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120823100819/http://www.london2012.com/wrestling/event/men-greco-roman-84kg/index.html#|archive-date=2012-08-23|url-status=dead}}</ref>\nThis [[Greco-Roman wrestling]] competition consists of a single-elimination tournament, with a [[repechage]] used to determine the winner of two bronze medals. The two finalists face off for gold and silver medals. Each wrestler who loses to one of the two finalists moves into the repechage, culminating in a pair of bronze medal matches featuring the semifinal losers each facing the remaining repechage opponent from their half of the bracket.\n\nEach bout consists of up to three rounds, lasting two minutes apiece. The wrestler who scores more points in each round is the winner of that rounds; the bout ends when one wrestler has won two rounds (and thus the match).\n\n==Schedule==\n<small>All times are [[British Summer Time]] ([[UTC+01:00]])</small>\n{|class = \"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! width=150|Date\n! width=50|Time\n! width=150|Event\n|-\n| rowspan=3| 6 August 2012 || 13:00 || Qualification rounds\n|-\n| 17:45 || Repechage\n|-\n| 18:30 || bgcolor=ffffcc|Finals\n|}\n\n==Results==\n;Legend\n*'''F''' \u2014 Won by [[Pin (amateur wrestling)|fall]]\n\n===Final===\n{{2TeamBracket-Tennis3\n| seeds = no\n| RD1=Final\n| nowrap = no\n\n| team-width=205\n| score-width=15\n| RD1-team1='''{{flagIOCathlete|[[Alan Khugaev]]|RUS|2012 Summer}}'''\n| RD1-score1-1='''1'''\n| RD1-score1-2='''2'''\n| RD1-score1-3=&nbsp;\n| RD1-team2={{flagIOCathlete|[[Karam Gaber]]|EGY|2012 Summer}}\n| RD1-score2-1=0\n| RD1-score2-2=0\n| RD1-score2-3=&nbsp;\n}}\n\n===Top half===\n{{16TeamBracket-Compact-Wrestling\n| RD1=Qualifications\n| RD2=1/8 finals\n| RD3=Quarterfinals\n| RD4=Semifinals\n\n| team-width=180\n| score-width=15\n\n| RD2-team01='''{{flagIOCathlete|[[Vladimer Gegeshidze]]|GEO|2012 Summer}}'''\n| RD2-score01-1='''2'''\n| RD2-score01-2=0\n| RD2-score01-3='''1'''\n| RD2-team02={{flagIOCathlete|[[Saman Tahmasebi]]|AZE|2012 Summer}}\n| RD2-score02-1=0\n| RD2-score02-2='''3'''\n| RD2-score02-3=0\n\n| RD2-team03='''{{flagIOCathlete|[[Vasyl Rachyba]]|UKR|2012 Summer}}'''\n| RD2-score03-1='''2'''\n| RD2-score03-2='''1'''\n| RD2-score03-3=&nbsp;\n| RD2-team04={{flagIOCathlete|[[Haykel Achouri]]|TUN|2012 Summer}}\n| RD2-score04-1=0\n| RD2-score04-2=0\n| RD2-score04-3=&nbsp;\n\n| RD2-team05='''{{flagIOCathlete|[[Alan Khugaev]]|RUS|2012 Summer}}'''\n| RD2-score05-1='''1'''\n| RD2-score05-2='''1'''\n| RD2-score05-3=&nbsp;\n| RD2-team06={{flagIOCathlete|[[Alim Selimau]]|BLR|2012 Summer}}\n| RD2-score06-1=0\n| RD2-score06-2=0\n| RD2-score06-3=&nbsp;\n\n| RD2-team07={{flagIOCathlete|[[Hristo Marinov]]|BUL|2012 Summer}}\n| RD2-score07-1=0\n| RD2-score07-2=0\n| RD2-score07-3=&nbsp;\n| RD2-team08='''{{flagIOCathlete|[[Daniyal Gadzhiyev]]|KAZ|2012 Summer}}'''\n| RD2-s